content.text: The below quality guide is based on the following established quality assessment checklist:
If so, please add relevant weblink for the trial protocol here:
11. Could the new test be successfully used with people and service-users (or population) of interest with good impact?
12.Were all the measured outcomes in the study important to the individual or wider population considered?
13.Were there any other issues or problems with the study in terms of bias or limitations we should know about? (please state below)
Can the results be used with people using local services?

How sure are we about the results? Did the authors provide calculations to show how precise the test is? Were there any costs and (hopefully beneficial!) outcomes of using the new diagnostic checklist?
Were the ways the new diagnostic test was used described in enough detail?
Was the health status of the tested group of people in the study (and wider population with the diagnosis) clearly described by the authors?

Could the results of the new diagnostic test or checklist have been influenced by the results of the “gold standard” one? Were the researchers giving the test aware of the test they gave people, or were they ‘blinded’?
Did all people in the study complete the new and “gold standard” diagnostic test or checklist?
Was the new diagnostic test or checklist compared to an appropriate “gold standard” or widely accepted test or checklist?

Did the authors publicly share a detailed plan or ‘protocol’ of how they would go about doing the study before they completed it? If they did, did they stick closely to the plan in the final study publication?
Did the study try to answer a clear and focused question or issue?
